How did viewing a diff between two versions of a file help you see the bug that
was introduced?

    The diff compare between the two files in details so you can check through
    it on all the differences between the files which make it easier to find
    the bugs

How could having easy access to the entire history of a file make you a more
efficient programmer in the long term?

    comparing history helps in the reflection journey where you process what
    you learn and asset your development

What do you think are the pros and cons of manually choosing when to create a
commit, like you do in Git, vs having versions automatically saved, like Google
docs does?

    Git > pros : always aware of when you need it, apply it on purpose
    cons : missing on important history or saving loads of data

    Google > pros : always saved
    cons : loads of data, important and not important ones

Why do you think some version control systems, like Git, allow saving multiple
files in one commit, while others, like Google Docs, treat each file separately?

    Git deals with the whole repository but Google Docs deals with each file

How can you use the commands git log and git diff to view the history of files?

    use commit log to check out all the commits done in the file, and compare
    two files using git diff to specify the exact changes

How might using version control make you more confident to make changes that
could break something?

    easily getting back to previous versions and know exactly what's wrong

Now that you have your workspace set up, what do you want to try using Git for?

    initially in the course
